english:
  title: Chongju on the Ninth Day, Sent to Jurchen
  author: Chen Hua
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last year on the ninth day at Autumn Clarity Pavilion—
    Maple leaves reddened in late frost, the lake's face grown pale.
    Young maidens bore wine to honor the finest guest,
    Rubbing chrysanthemum fragrance between their hands, steeping amber cups.

    On painted railings, delicate wisps of dogwood smoke curled—
    The drunken eye, unaware, bloomed red.
    The old traces of Jiangdong fade in a moment's breath,
    Yet today I wander at heaven's western edge.

    South of Yuyang, no mountains meet the sight,
    Only mosquito thunder from a country inn gathers like leopard tracks.
    Forceful drinking by the roadside yields no joy,
    The short day's crimson haze deepens only sorrow.

    Only the western wind preserves its ancient manner,
    Whispering softly, shaking the black gauze hat to fall.
  footnotes:
    - Chongju refers to the journey to the Jurchen court; the ninth day is the Double Ninth Festival, traditionally a day of celebration and reunion in Chinese-Korean tradition.
    - The contrast between last year's refined celebration and present loneliness structures the poem's emotional arc.
    - Western wind and falling hat suggest the poet's displacement and loss of status on diplomatic journey.
